It's the copy of the movie that is sent from movie studios to movie theaters to allow them to see it before they 'buy' it and show it in their theater(s).  It's the TeleSync's/TeleCene's(sp?) and CAM copies that are usually crap quality..  grainy video and scratchy sound on most of them. I use Peerguardian.  Doesn't it compile a list and block out ip's it knows to track this sort of thing, such as blocking Comcast from seeing what I'm downloading?

It is not actually your ISP that catches you, it's RIAA, or another organization as such, that downloads and tracks all seeders by their IP addresses.  You can FORCE encryption, but that only means your ISP can't see what's in the packets you send out, but the receiver still gets the packets.  Usually, the copyright owner, or whoever is doing it, grabs 1K to less than 1K of the file you are seeding, which is enough.  PeerBlock and other such programs only work if it has the right IP addresses to block.  You cannot stop uploading, and if you do, that's a pretty crappy way of doing things.  You would have to block the port your Torrent client is using, which will block incoming connections for outbound traffic.
